Diagnosis. Separated from
A. schusteri
by having males with the embolus distinctly bent perpendicular to prolateral side of the tarsus (
Figs. 104, 105, 108
) and with a broad median sclerite (
Fig. 104, 107
). Females with spermathecae that are approximately twice as long as wide and with broad bases (
Fig. 110
).

Abdomen pale, without pattern, 0.79 long, 0.56 wide. Spermathecae slightly longer than wide and with wide bases (
Fig. 110
).

Distribution. Known from localities in Amador, Calaveras, El Dorado, and Placer counties (
Fig. 115
).
